Trump said his plans for a Muslim ban hadn't changed, but he's now framing it differently: instead of a ban on Muslims, it's a ban on travel from dangerous territories. [According](http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/316726-giuliani-trump-asked-me-how-to-do-a-muslim-ban-legally
) to Trump surrogate Rudy Giuliani, Trump arrived at this solution after asking his team "the right way" to do a Muslim ban "legally." In his public statements on this shift, Trump implied that he was aware of the constitutional problems with his ban, but believes national security is more important.

It is unclear if Trump understood the potential constitutional issues with his ban for violating due process rights of U.S. residents; nonetheless, he addressed the issue of whether or not the ban would apply to residents during his campaign. Trump again made shifting statements, first saying the ban will apply to American Muslims abroad, then clarifying it will not apply to U.S. citizens and residents:


http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/262348-trump-calls-for-shutdown-of-muslims-entering-us
	Trump, in a formal statement from his campaign, urged a “total and complete shutdown” of all federal processes allowing followers of Islam into the country until elected leaders can “figure out what is going on.”

	Asked by The Hill whether that would include American Muslims currently abroad, Trump spokeswoman Hope Hicks replied over email: “Mr. Trump says, ‘everyone.’ ”

	During a Tuesday morning interview with ABC's "Good Morning America," however, Trump clarified that American Muslims would still be able to travel freely under his plan.

	"If a person is a Muslim and goes overseas and come back, they can come back. They are a citizen, that is different," Trump said. 


http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1512/07/cnnt.01.html
