- In Louhghalam v. Trump, petitioner lawyers argue 




Even still, barring reentry for LPRs might not need to have been a death sentence for the travel ban. Records obtained by FOIA show that in the first few hours of its implementation, CBP developed a policy of allowing LPRs to enter the country under a waiver provision in the executive order. According to a DHS FAQ released on February 2nd, the CBP admitted 1,600 LPRs into the country through the EO's waiver provision. Records and media reports also show that CBP at least attempt to provide guidance to airlines that LPRs should be allowed to board flights to the U.S. The administration would therefore be able to argue that any LPRs barred from returning home were done so in error. This might not have saved the ban from being struck down as unconstitutional on the grounds of its application to LPRs (as Tawfeeq v. DHS pointed out, this policy left LPRs reentry at CBP's discretion with no opportunity to appeal), but it could be used to argue a TRO wasn't urgently needed.


